> Another important note: In C, an int is 4 bytes, in E it is only 2.  You
> shoudl replace all INT's with LONG's, unless you want a C short.

To be exact:

In C it is not defined if an int is 16 or 32 bit. This is completely
compiler
specific.
And this is the cause that "exec/types.c" exists: it defines the macros
LONG,
INT etc. that should always be used when writing C programs on Amiga.

But I think (but this maybe false) most Amiga C compilers use 16 bit (2
bytes) to store an integer (or short integer), 32 bit (4 bytes) to store a
long integer and 8 bit (1 byte) to store a char.

Again: To answer this question correctly have a look in the ANSI-C
definition, there is a range of number of bits each datatype can have.
If you really want to know how many bits/bytes an C datatype has, you must
know for wich compiler it is designed!

Ciao, Alfred

