@node ID14_2 "Best way to use two-dimensional array in Amiga-E ? (ID14_2)"
Date: Sun, 18 Oct 1998 17:38:16 +0100 (GMT)
From: tim@oakley.keble.ox.ac.uk (Tim Bagot)
Subject: Re: Best way to use two-dimensional array in Amiga-E ?

On Sun, 18 Oct 1998, Norbert Roth wrote:

> Hello,
>
> just a simple question.
>
> In E there isn't such thing as a size of an array,
> so there's no way to use two-dimensional arrays
> in the common way of sense.
>
> What is the best way to handle such arrays,
> e.g. a 'huge' stiffnes matrix ?
>
> Thanks in advance for any suggestions.

It depends on what exactly you want to do.

The simplest is just to use a 1d array of length xsize*ysize and use
y*xsize + x as the index.

If you want it to know its size, you could use something like:-

OBJECT array2d
  xsize
  ysize
  data:PTR TO type
ENDOBJECT

Where data would point to a block of memory with length
xsize * ysize * SIZEOF type.

Alternatively you could just use a list: [ xsize , ysize , data ], where
data could be a simple 1d array, or a list.

Another way is to nest an x array inside each element of a y array, using
the array form of your choice.

HTH

Tim Bagot

@endnode

