That'd be a cut-down version of the Beginner's Guide.  You can find
the full version in the Docs directory in the full Amiga E
distribution (the latest version of Amiga E is v3.3a).  It includes
a few bigger examples, the source code for which is in the Src/Guide
directory.

> I've got dozens of other little bits and pieces that are supposed to
> be manuals, but turn out to be reference manuals instead.

Yes, I guess most people have already been exposed to Amiga
programming (using C, probably) and so the big demand is for language
manuals for Amiga E.

> I need a more step by step guide to E. For instance, telling me how
> to open a basic window, how to pull imput and write it to a file, how
> to keep a window updated as the enduser adds text.

What you're talking about here is not specific to Amiga E.  You're
asking "How do I program the Amiga?"  The official manuals are called
the Rom Kernel Reference Manuals, which is a five volume set.  The
best one is the Libraries edition, as recommended by the Beginner's
Guide (you really ought to read it, you know...).

The RKRMs use examples in C, but there are also E versions, which
(surprisingly) you'll find in the Src/Rkrm directory.  Once you know
the Amiga E language (see the Beginner's Guide) you might find it
worthwhile to look at the E versions of the RKRM code, and maybe
pick up a copy of the RKRMs.  I believe you can get electronic
(AmigaGuide) versions of the RKRMs on the Amiga Developer's CD 1.2.

> Is there anywhere in this whole wide world that actually teaches AmigaE?

The Beginner's Guide is about the only thing out there (for Amiga E).
The RKRMs are about the best things for learning general Amiga
programming.

But, if someone was willing to pay me a decent salary for, say, the
next ten years, I'd be more than willing to start a school.  ;-)

