On Wed, 21 Oct 1998, David Arbuthnot wrote:

> Hi i a newbie to this list and i am wondering how to use the Fwrite
> and Fread functions multiple times ???
> If possible please could I have an example please.

Don't know if I have undestood your question, and I don't have my RKRM
here, however I will try.

Fwrite and Fread are *buffered* functions to access files. They work
differently from Write and Read as they use blocks instead of normal
bytes.
Apart this difference, hoever, there is not difference in their use. You
can just send multiple data out with multiple Fwrite commands, this way:

Fwrite(fh, buf, 4, 3) -> should write 12 bytes that is 3 times 4 bytes
Fwrite(fh, buf+12, 1, 10) -> should write the next 1*10 bytes in buf

and so on.

Remember that the buf pointer must be updated every time you use the
Fwrite function if you are going to write data from the same buffer or you
are going to write always the same data.

The same for Fread, but this time you have to make sure you are not going
to overwrite the same data in the next Fread calls.

Es:

DEF buf[64]:ARRY OF CHAR, tmp=NIL
DEF fh=NIL:filehandle -> You obtain this from an Open() function

tmp:=buf
Fread(fh, tmp, 4, 3) -> We are reading the first 12 bytes from the
                     -> filehandle
tmp := tmp+12        -> Update the position in the buffer
Fread(fh, tmp, 2 ,5) -> Reading the next 5 INT (10 bytes) from the
                     -> filehandle

And go on.

Be ALWAYS sure that you don't go outside the buf size otherwise... well
you know 8).

Remeber also to NEVER use the buffered DOS functions together the
not-buffered function on the same filehandle or you are going to get a
real mess. Probably a Flush() function to flush the OS device buffer
between the passage from the buffer to not-buffered functions and
viceversa should be enough, but I have never tried that (the use of
buffered and unbuffered function on the same file at the same time can be
avoided and, IMHO, must be avoided to not have to solve the problems that
may araise). Moreover buffered functions should always be used when
possible, especially for very small data transerfs (few bytes). They are
much faster (even 5 or more time faster).

Don't know if that may be useful to you. But I hope so.

M&F

