>     y:=s.height-ysize/2
>
>   ENDIF
>
> I presume the mucking about with the viewports is to get knowledge of
> the visible portions of the screen, but that [h] could be a problem,
> and I've tried a few alternatives that all crashed :(

Yeah, the tricky bit of code involving "h" is nasty (reusing the
variable) but necessary since the list is static and VideoControl()
(as the comment suggests) thinks it's OK for it to alter the list
it's passed.  [I've noticed that a number of system routines that
take tag lists think they own them...]

Of course, using a static list in a library is a big No-No.  What
you want to do is make a copy.  Something like:

  -> Remember to handle the exception if NEW fails
  h:=NEW [VTAG_VIEWPORTEXTRA_GET, NIL, NIL]
  IF (IF cm:=s.viewport.colormap THEN VideoControl(cm,h) BUT
               vpe:=h[1] ELSE vpe:=NIL)
    ...
  ELSE
    ...
  ENDIF
  -> Remember to deallocate it once you're done
  FastDisposeList(h)

> Also, what does this do? (from findxy()):
>
>     IF x>=(gad.leftedge+offx) THEN
>     IF y>=(gad.topedge+offy) THEN
>     IF gad.leftedge+gad.width>x THEN
>     IF gad.topedge+gad.height>y THEN RETURN gad.userdata
>
> If this is simple bounds-checking (i.e. a point within a box), shouldn't
> a simpler way of expressing this be used?

E doesn't have short-cut "AND" and "OR" so I wrote it like this to
mimic that.  It's basically lots of ANDs that stop as soon as one of
them is FALSE, so you don't do any unnecessary processing.  Neat, eh?
Not sure if it actually produces better or worse code than simply
using AND, though.  ;-)  [Ask Wouter?]

> In terms of progress with the transition to a library, almost all of the
